        <title>Sales Management in a Down Economy - Part Three</title>
        <link rel="alternate" type="text/html" href="http://www.intelligentconversations.com/b2b_sales_intelligent_con/2008/11/sales-management-in-a-down-economy-part-three.html" />
        <link rel="replies" type="text/html" href="http://www.intelligentconversations.com/b2b_sales_intelligent_con/2008/11/sales-management-in-a-down-economy-part-three.html" thr:count="0" />
        <id>tag:typepad.com,2003:post-59024208</id>
        <published>2008-11-25T09:58:32-06:00</published>
        <updated>2008-11-25T10:00:02-06:00</updated>
        <summary>Our third and final post on Sales Management in a Down Economy is all about motivation. Being a sales professional is a tough and demanding job. Being a sales professional in a challenging economy will be even harder. As sales...</summary>
        <author>
            <name>mikecarroll</name>
        </author>
        <category scheme="http://www.sixapart.com/ns/types#category" term="Sales Management" />
        
        
<content type="xhtml" xml:lang="en-US" xml:base="http://www.intelligentconversations.com/b2b_sales_intelligent_con/">
<div xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"><p class="MsoNormal">Our third and final post on Sales Management in a Down Economy is all about motivation.&#0160; Being a sales professional is a tough and demanding
job.<span>&#0160; </span>Being a sales professional in a
challenging economy will be even harder.<span>&#0160;
</span>As sales manager it is your job to make sure every person on your team
is mentally prepared to do their day.<span>&#0160; </span>As
you are conducting your pre-call planning or post-call debriefing sessions be
aware of sales people who seem distracted or disengaged.<span>&#0160; </span>Make sure they have their head on straight
before they go out to make their calls.</p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><o:p>&#0160;</o:p></p>

<ul style="margin-top: 0in;" type="disc"><li class="MsoNormal">Do you
 understand what motivates each person on your sales team?<span>&#0160; </span>Everyone has different levers to
 pull.<span>&#0160; </span>For some it may be public
 recognition in a sales meeting.<span>&#0160; </span>For
 others it may be an afternoon off to spend with their families.<span>&#0160; </span>Make sure you know what motivates the
 individuals on your team and then apply that motivation as necessary.</li>
<li class="MsoNormal">Watch
 for seasonal patterns.<span>&#0160; </span>Many sales
 people are insecure and will go through bouts of depression or self
 doubt.<span>&#0160; </span>A good way to monitor this
 is to look for periods of slower production and then subtract your typical
 sales cycle.<span>&#0160; </span>So if you have someone
 who does poorly in May and you have a six month sales cycle, watch their
 behavior in December and help them stay focused and motivated.</li>
<li class="MsoNormal">Talk
 to your team every day.<span>&#0160; </span>Hold a 20
 minute ???sales huddle??? every morning (stand up in a conference room or have
 people dial into a bridge line) to make sure everyone is aligned for the
 day.<span>&#0160; </span>Walk around or make brief
 phone calls to check in with people.<span>&#0160;
 </span>This does not need to be formal, just touch base and listen to how
 they sound and find out how they are doing.</li>
</ul>

<p class="MsoNormal"><o:p>&#0160;</o:p></p>

<p class="MsoNormal">Sales managers will play a crucial role in helping their
companies navigate through tough economic times.<span>&#0160; </span>Creating a culture of accountability, raising
expectations and motivating sales people to stretch beyond their comfort zone
will be more critical than ever.</p></div>
</content>


