    <entry>
        <title>Sales Management in a Down Economy - Part Two</title>
        <link rel="alternate" type="text/html" href="http://www.intelligentconversations.com/b2b_sales_intelligent_con/2008/11/sales-management-in-a-down-economy-1.html" />
        <link rel="replies" type="text/html" href="http://www.intelligentconversations.com/b2b_sales_intelligent_con/2008/11/sales-management-in-a-down-economy-1.html" thr:count="0" />
        <id>tag:typepad.com,2003:post-58665152</id>
        <published>2008-11-18T07:19:13-06:00</published>
        <updated>2008-11-21T15:00:51-06:00</updated>
        <summary>This is our second of three posts focused on Sales Management in a Down Economy. Our goal is to review the three things you absolutely must do as sales manager if you want your sales team to continue to thrive...</summary>
        <author>
            <name>mikecarroll</name>
        </author>
        <category scheme="http://www.sixapart.com/ns/types#category" term="Sales Management" />
        
        
<content type="xhtml" xml:lang="en-US" xml:base="http://www.intelligentconversations.com/b2b_sales_intelligent_con/">
<div xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"><p style="font-size: 14px; font-family: Times New Roman;">This is our second of three posts focused on Sales Management in a Down Economy.&#0160; Our goal is to review the three things you absolutely must do as sales
manager if you want your sales team to continue to thrive and succeed -
no matter what the headlines say about our current economy.</p><p style="font-size: 14px; font-family: Times New Roman;">An area we often see our clients struggle (in any economy) is sales coaching.&#0160; </p>



<p style="font-size: 14px; font-family: Times New Roman;">Effective coaching really means holding pre-call planning sessions
and post-call debriefing sessions with every single sales person, every
day.<span>&#0160; </span>You can quickly and dramatically
change the behaviors of your sales team with effective questioning before and
after their sales calls.<span>&#0160; </span>Questions for a
pre-call planning session might look like this:<o:p> <br /></o:p></p>

<ul style="margin-top: 0in; font-family: inherit;" type="disc"><li class="MsoNormal" style="font-family: inherit;"><p style="margin-top: 0in; font-size: 14px; font-family: Times New Roman;">Where
 does this call need to end for you to consider it a success?</p></li>
<li class="MsoNormal">What
 do we know about their budget?<span>&#0160; </span>Are
 there other financial options or resources available to them?</li>
<li class="MsoNormal">Where
 does our product or service rank in terms of their overall priorities?</li>
<li class="MsoNormal">When
 is the last time they made a decision of this magnitude?<span>&#0160; </span>How did they make that decision?<span>&#0160; </span>Who was involved?<span>&#0160; </span>Do we fully understand their decision
 process for our product or service?</li>
<li class="MsoNormal">What
 is the cost of doing nothing?<span>&#0160; </span>What
 are the consequences (business, economic, political and personal) of not
 making a decision?<o:p> <br /></o:p></li>
</ul>



<p style="font-size: 14px; font-family: Times New Roman;">The post-call debriefing questions will be similar, but will
look back instead of forward (Where did the call end? What is their budget?
etc.).</p><p style="font-size: 14px; font-family: Times New Roman;"></p><p style="font-size: 14px; font-family: Times New Roman;"></p><p style="font-size: 14px; font-family: Times New Roman;">How are you doing when it comes to consistent, daily coaching conversations with every member of your team?&#0160; What can you do, starting today, to redouble your efforts to sit down with team members for effective pre-call planning and post-call debrief sessions?&#0160; In a challenging economy - where resistance is high and prospective clients are more likely than ever to stall or delay buying decisions - your sales team needs this attention now more than ever.</p>

<p></p></div>
</content>


