        <updated>2008-11-19T16:46:16-06:00</updated>
        <summary>Our next three posts will focus on Sales Management in a Down Economy. Here&#39;s the first of three things you absolutely must do as sales manager if you want your sales team to continue to thrive and succeed - no...</summary>
        <author>
            <name>mikecarroll</name>
        </author>
        <category scheme="http://www.sixapart.com/ns/types#category" term="Sales Management" />
        
        
<content type="xhtml" xml:lang="en-US" xml:base="http://www.intelligentconversations.com/b2b_sales_intelligent_con/">
<div xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"><p>Our next three posts will focus on Sales Management in a Down Economy.&#0160; Here&#39;s the first of three things you absolutely must do as sales manager if you want your sales team to continue to thrive and succeed - no matter what the headlines say about our current economy.</p><p>1. Hold your sales team accountable</p><p>What are you measuring and how often are you measuring it?&#0160; Holding your sales team accountable means being more demanding than ever before by measuring specific behaviors and activities for every sales person, every day.&#0160; If you manage the right behaviors, results will follow.&#0160; </p><p>The best way to start is to work backwards through your sales pipeline to understand your critical sales ratios, both for your team and for individual sales people. &#0160; Start with the number of new opportunities you need, then work backwards from there.</p><ul>
<li>Number of new orders (or new customers) required per month: _____ </li>
<li>Number of qualified opportunities to hit the required number of new orders (you can base this on historical closing ratios by sales person) : _____ </li>
<li>Number of qualified prospects to hit the required number of opportunities: _____ </li>
<li>Number of appointments to hit the required number of prospects: _____ </li>
<li>Number of calls or referrals to hit the required number of appointments: _____ </li>
</ul>
<p>Once you understand these critical sales ratios ??? for both your team and for each sales person ??? you can begin to measure and manage the behaviors required to drive the results you need. </p><p>Let???s say one of your sales people needs three new orders per month hit their sales goal and it takes six qualified opportunities per month to hit that goal (based on a 50% closing ratio), and it takes 10 prospects to get six opportunities, and it takes 20 appointments to get 10 qualified prospects, and it takes 60 calls or referrals to get 20 appointments.&#0160; If these are the critical sales ratios for your sales person, you can monitor their calls and appointments every day to make sure they stay on track.&#0160;

And once you understand this for each team member, you can easily spot potential problems before you get to the end of the month or quarter.&#0160;&#0160; Step one is to know your critical sales ratios and hold your team accountable to them every day.
</p></div>
</content>


