        <title>Lessons from Living as a Leader Presentation</title>
        <link rel="alternate" type="text/html" href="http://www.intelligentconversations.com/b2b_sales_intelligent_con/2008/09/lessons-from-living-as-a-leader-presentation.html" />
        <link rel="replies" type="text/html" href="http://www.intelligentconversations.com/b2b_sales_intelligent_con/2008/09/lessons-from-living-as-a-leader-presentation.html" thr:count="2" thr:updated="2008-10-04T15:39:21-05:00" />
        <id>tag:typepad.com,2003:post-55086166</id>
        <published>2008-09-03T13:34:37-05:00</published>
        <updated>2008-10-04T15:39:21-05:00</updated>
        <summary>Yesterday I had the opportunity to listen to Aleta Norris of Impact Consulting make a rather boring topic - employee appraisals - really interesting. I&#39;m always amazed by the niches people find for themselves and love learning from someone who...</summary>
        <author>
            <name>mikecarroll</name>
        </author>
        <category scheme="http://www.sixapart.com/ns/types#category" term="Sales Coaching" />
        
        
<content type="xhtml" xml:lang="en-US" xml:base="http://www.intelligentconversations.com/b2b_sales_intelligent_con/">
<div xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"><p style="font-size: 13px; font-family: Helvetica;">Yesterday I had the opportunity to listen to Aleta Norris of <a href="http://www.impact-consulting.com/About.html">Impact Consulting</a> make a rather boring topic - employee appraisals - really interesting.&#160; I&#39;m always amazed by the niches people find for themselves and love learning from someone who brings a lot of knowledge and passion to their topic.&#160; Aleta delivered both and did an excellent job sharing her perspective as part of the <a href="http://www.kicktheeconomy.com/go/MikeCarroll">Kick the Economy</a> series.</p><p style="font-size: 13px; font-family: Helvetica;">Here&#39;s a summary of Aleta&#39;s recommendations on the right way to conduct an employee appraisal.&#160; Notice the parallels to the sales process.</p><ol style="font-family: inherit;">
<li style="font-family: inherit;"><p style="font-size: 13px; font-family: Helvetica;"><p style="font-size: 14px;"><span style="font-size: 14px;">Set the stage - build rapport, explain the meeting purpose, outline the discussion, get employee reaction.</span></p></p></li>
<li>Begin with the employee&#39;s perspective - ask open-ended questions, listen, don&#39;t add your ideas yet.</li>
<li>Add your ideas - compare your perspective to the employee&#39;s, support with examples, be specific, remember it&#39;s the first meeting not the last meeting.</li>
<li>Come to agreement - ask employee how they feel about your comments, be prepared to support your position, don&#39;t argue about numbers, come back to goals and definitions.</li>
<li>Help develop goals - ask the employee for ideas, add your own ideas, define goals.</li>
</ol>
<p style="font-size: 13px; font-family: Helvetica;">Earlier in her presentation Aleta noted that most employee appraisal meetings are one-sided, with the boss talking 80-90% of the time and little opportunity for employee input or reaction.&#160; Even the forms used in most employee evaluations tend to be fairly standard and require the boss to make everything fit into a box or fall onto a scale somewhere between 1 and 5.</p><p style="font-size: 13px; font-family: Helvetica;">How many sales meetings have you been in where you&#39;ve done all the talking (80-90%)? How many presentations have you made where you did a &quot;save as..&quot; and just changed the prospect name and logo (fitting everyone into a standard template).&#160;&#160; What would happen to your sales results if you followed Aleta&#39;s advice for a good employee appraisal (ask questions, listen, then build on what the prospect says)?&#160; Why not try it on your next call?</p></div>
</content>


    </entry>
