    <entry>
        <title>A-Players Only or Best Available?</title>
        <link rel="alternate" type="text/html" href="http://www.intelligentconversations.com/b2b_sales_intelligent_con/2008/08/a-players-only-or-best-available.html" />
        <link rel="replies" type="text/html" href="http://www.intelligentconversations.com/b2b_sales_intelligent_con/2008/08/a-players-only-or-best-available.html" thr:count="0" />
        <id>tag:typepad.com,2003:post-54306164</id>
        <published>2008-08-17T07:57:12-05:00</published>
        <updated>2008-08-17T16:35:09-05:00</updated>
        <summary>We???re working with several clients who are hiring sales people. One of the questions we ask as we help them set up our recruiting system is whether they want to have an ???A-Players Only??? policy. Nearly everyone says ???Yes, of...</summary>
        <author>
            <name>mikecarroll</name>
        </author>
        <category scheme="http://www.sixapart.com/ns/types#category" term="Sales Management" />
        
        
<content type="xhtml" xml:lang="en-US" xml:base="http://www.intelligentconversations.com/b2b_sales_intelligent_con/">
<div xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"><p style="font-size: 14px; font-family: Georgia;">We???re working with several clients who are hiring sales
people.&#160; One of the questions we ask as we help them set up our recruiting
system is whether they want to have an ???A-Players Only??? policy.&#160; Nearly
everyone says ???Yes, of course we only want to hire
A-Players.???&#160; While they are quick to agree with it, they may not fully
realize the impact this policy will have on their hiring process until they are
several steps into the process. </p>



<p style="font-size: 14px; font-family: Georgia;">An ???A-Player Only??? policy means you need to <span style="text-decoration: underline;">raise
expectations AND stick with the new standard</span>.&#160; When we work with
clients to help them hire A-Players, we lead our clients through a series of
questions to help determine the things a new sales person will need to have done
successfully in their past in order to thrive in our client???s sales
environment.&#160; This covers everything from the type of prospective clients
they???ve worked with in the past to the length and complexity of their sales
cycle, to their experience level, and several other important factors. </p>



<p style="font-size: 14px; font-family: Georgia;">Based on our client???s answers we are able to develop a
custom profile that helps set the new standard for an ???A-Player??? sales person
at their company.&#160; We then use this custom profile in the <a href="http://www.objectivemanagement.com/testus.htm">Dave Kurlan Express Screen</a>
and run all sales candidates through this pre-employment assessment.&#160; This
is an assessment tool that has been shown to have a 96% accuracy rating when
predicting the hirability of a sales candidate.&#160; It???s really, really good.</p><p style="font-size: 14px; font-family: Georgia;"><span style="font-size: 14px;">But it???s only this good if our clients use it
correctly.&#160; Recently we???ve seen clients continue to look at candidates
rated as ???unhirable??? based on the criteria they???ve set.&#160; This happens for
several reasons:&#160;</span></p>

<ul style="font-family: inherit;"><li style="font-family: inherit;"><p style="font-size: 14px;">The candidate gives a strong
performance in a group interview setting.</p></li>
<li><p style="font-size: 14px;">The candidate has relevant
experience at a competitor or with a company in a similar market space.</p></li>
<li><p style="font-size: 14px;">The hiring manager or business
owner ???has a feeling??? about the candidate. </p></li>
<li><p style="font-size: 14px;">The candidate ???could be hirable if
we changed some of our criteria.??? </p></li>
<li><p style="font-size: 14px;">The hiring process has taken
longer than expected and the hiring manager starts feeling&#160;pressure to
fill the position as quickly as possible.<br />
</p></li>
</ul>











<p style="font-size: 14px; font-family: Georgia;">All of these reasons may be valid and true.&#160; And all
point to the challenge of sticking with a high standard for ???A-Players
Only.???&#160; Many of the ???unhirable??? candidates my clients are considering may
be capable of producing good results in the short term.&#160; And not all of
the candidates rated as ???hirable??? should be hired simply because the assessment
says so (they still need to be a good cultural match for my client, they need
to demonstrate passion, commitment and enthusiasm for their business, etc.). </p>



<p style="font-size: 14px; font-family: Georgia;">What it comes down to is do you truly want to hire
???A-Players Only??? or do you simply want to settle for the ???Best Available???
candidate?&#160; For some businesses ??? particularly those in a phase of rapid
growth and expansion ??? a ???Best Available??? policy may be the way to go.&#160;
And if the right systems and processes are in place to support the sales team
once they???re on board, this approach can be very successful.&#160; But which
policy will produce better results in the long term?&#160; In our experience,
it&#39;s a lot easier to grow your business and increase revenue when you have a
sales team consisting of &quot;A-Players&quot; who not only can sell, but
actually will sell and will thrive at your company.</p><p style="font-size: 14px; font-family: Georgia;">What???s your policy for hiring sales people?&#160; Have you
set your expectations high enough?&#160; As you look at your current team and
some of the challenges you face, could it be the results of ???settling??? for the
best available candidate when you hired them?&#160; Do you have a recruiting
policy in place to upgrade these positions?&#160; If not, what are you waiting
for?</p></div>
</content>


    </entry>
    <entry>
        <title>Telling Great Stories</title>
        <link rel="alternate" type="text/html" href="http://www.intelligentconversations.com/b2b_sales_intelligent_con/2008/08/telling-great-stories.html" />
        <link rel="replies" type="text/html" href="http://www.intelligentconversations.com/b2b_sales_intelligent_con/2008/08/telling-great-stories.html" thr:count="0" />
        <id>tag:typepad.com,2003:post-54240574</id>
        <published>2008-08-15T12:50:53-05:00</published>
        <updated>2008-08-17T16:31:27-05:00</updated>
        <summary>Our business at Intelligent Conversations is fairly complex. Our elevator pitch is ???We work with Presidents, CEOs and Business Owners to dramatically increase top line growth by improving the people, systems and strategies that impact sales.??? But when you drill...</summary>
        <author>
            <name>mikecarroll</name>
        </author>
        <category scheme="http://www.sixapart.com/ns/types#category" term="Sales Coaching" />
        
        
<content type="xhtml" xml:lang="en-US" xml:base="http://www.intelligentconversations.com/b2b_sales_intelligent_con/">
<div xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"><p style="font-size: 15px; font-family: Georgia;">Our business at Intelligent Conversations is fairly
complex.<span>&#160; </span>Our elevator pitch is ???We work
with Presidents, CEOs and Business Owners to dramatically increase top line
growth by improving the people, systems and strategies that impact sales.???<span>&#160;</span><o:p> <br /></o:p></p>



<p style="font-size: 15px; font-family: Georgia;">But when you drill down a level and begin to look at all the
things we do ??? from recruiting and on-boarding new sales people, to coaching
and helping sales managers create a culture of accountability, to optimizing
sales systems and CRM workflows, to making pipeline reports more useful and
meaningful, to developing custom databases of target prospects, to redesigning
sales meetings to be more efficient and effective, to implementing on-going
skills training and development programs, to designing compensation plans that
motivate sales people and attract better talent, to market development, lead
generation and nurture programs that fill the funnel with qualified opportunities and on and on ??? it can get very complex, very
quickly.<o:p> <br /></o:p></p>



<p style="font-size: 15px; font-family: Georgia;">How do you break through this complexity and help a busy CEO
???get it??? quickly?<span>&#160; </span>One way is to have
great stories to share.<span> Stories that provide</span> specific
examples and real results that capture their attention.<span>&#160;</span><o:p> <br /></o:p></p>



<p style="font-size: 15px; font-family: Georgia;">For our business I like to tell the story about a prospect
who called me (based on a referral from another client) wanting to buy a lead
generation program.<span>&#160; </span>She was ready to
spend a lot of money to buy qualified leads from us because her sales team was not
generating enough activity on their own.<o:p> <br /></o:p></p>



<p style="font-size: 15px; font-family: Georgia;">I asked her lots of questions.<span>&#160; </span>Some of which she couldn???t answer.<span>&#160; </span>And then I suggested the first thing we
should do is assess their sales team and look at their current sales
environment to make sure a lead program would work.<span>&#160; </span>She was floored ??? she wanted to write a check
and solve the problem and I wouldn???t take her money.<o:p> <br /></o:p></p>







<p style="font-size: 15px; font-family: Georgia;">But when we took a step back and completed the assessment,
we uncovered a host of issues that would need to be addressed before investing
in a lead generation program would make sense.<span>&#160;
</span>After working with this client for several months, she thanked me for
not taking her money when she first called.<span>&#160;
</span>In that time period she came to understand that the program she wanted
to buy would have failed.</p><p style="font-size: 15px; font-family: Georgia;"><o:p></o:p>As I???ve told this story to prospective customers, it seems
to resonate because:<br /><o:p> </o:p></p>

<ul style="font-family: inherit;"><li style="font-family: inherit;"><span style="font-size: 15px; font-family: Georgia;"><p style="font-size: 16px;">They quickly relate to the executive who called me and wanted a quick
fix to her sales challenges (and how she was reacting to the symptom, not the problem).</p></span></li>
<li><p style="font-size: 15px;">It demonstrates a key part of our culture and how we do
business by taking the best interests of our clients to heart.<o:p></o:p>&#160; And it builds credibility by showing how we were ready to walk
away from a large order.</p></li>
<li><p style="font-size: 15px;">And it creates an opening for further conversation ???
inevitably people want to know more about the issues we uncovered when we
assessed this client and how we???re addressing them.&#160; And that???s a great conversation for us to
have.</p><o:p> </o:p></li>
</ul>















<p style="font-size: 15px; font-family: Georgia;">What stories do you tell in your sales process?<span>&#160; </span>Do you have great examples to share?<span>&#160; </span>It???s one thing to go through your carefully
designed PowerPoint presentation.<span>&#160; </span>But
how much more effective will you be if you can tell a great story about how you
helped a customer in a similar situation?<span>&#160;&#160;
</span>Why not try it on your next call?</p></div>
</content>


    </entry>
