	mso-fareast-language:#0400;
	mso-bidi-language:#0400;}
&lt;/style&gt;
&lt;![endif]--&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I&#39;m a huge Red Sox fan and will dearly miss the clutch hitting and majestic
home runs Manny Ramirez has delivered over the past 8 years.&amp;nbsp; But I won&#39;t
miss watching him jog to first base or feign injuries during key games.&lt;o:p&gt;&lt;/o:p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;When I heard the news of his trade to the Dodgers yesterday, it sparked an
idea for a post about when to let your top producer go.&amp;nbsp; Well, apparently
it sparked the same idea for other bloggers too.&amp;nbsp; Here&#39;s a link to what my
friend and mentor &lt;a target=&quot;_blank&quot; href=&quot;http://tinyurl.com/5j88vj&quot;&gt;Dave Kurlan&lt;/a&gt; has to
say about this latest development in&amp;nbsp;&lt;st1:city w:st=&quot;on&quot;&gt;&lt;/st1:city&gt;Boston and how it may apply to your sales team.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;o:p&gt;&lt;/o:p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;While it&#39;s tough to take a great hitter like Manny out of your line-up, I
support Theo Epstein&#39;s decision to put the team first.&amp;nbsp; One of the keys to
building a winning team is to have the same rules for everyone.&amp;nbsp; Another
is to have 100% inclusion and involvement.&amp;nbsp; Manny being Manny undercuts
both of these rules.&amp;nbsp; When a star player decides he doesn&#39;t need to do
things the same way everyone else does; when they decide they don&#39;t need to
follow the same rules and can choose when they want to be involved or not,
they&#39;re putting their own needs ahead of the team.&lt;o:p&gt;&lt;/o:p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;We can switch sports for another example.&amp;nbsp; What has happened to the USA
Basketball Team in International Competition over the past several years?&amp;nbsp;
Our invincible &quot;collection of All-Stars&quot; has been thumped
consistently by less talented players who have learned to play together as a
team and follow the same system.&amp;nbsp; It&#39;s all about execution and everyone
understanding their role within a system.&amp;nbsp; And great systems allow
average-to-slightly-above-average talent to produce outstanding results.&lt;o:p&gt;&lt;/o:p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I don&#39;t know what will happen in Beijing this month.&amp;nbsp; There&#39;s no doubt that Team USA has better talent.&amp;nbsp; But
are they a better team?&amp;nbsp; We&#39;ll have to watch what happens.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;o:p&gt;&lt;/o:p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt; font-family: &amp;quot;Times New Roman&amp;quot;;&quot;&gt;How about your sales team?&amp;nbsp; Do you have anyone on
your sales team acting like Manny Ramirez?&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt; font-family: &amp;quot;Times New Roman&amp;quot;;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp; Do you have someone who feels their
production and performance will inoculate them from negative consequences?&amp;nbsp;
If so, are you prepared to let them go (and lose their production) for the good
of your team?&amp;nbsp; It&#39;s a hard decision, but one that great sales managers are
prepared to make&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
</content>


    </entry>
