&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;Is your sales team getting a lot of objections from
prospects?&lt;span&gt;&amp;nbsp; &lt;/span&gt;That???s good!&amp;nbsp; It means
they???re having meaningful conversations.&lt;span&gt;&amp;nbsp;
&lt;/span&gt;Too often we think of objections as a negative sign ??? an obstacle we
need to overcome or get around.&lt;span&gt;&amp;nbsp; &lt;/span&gt;But if your
team isn???t generating objections from prospects on a daily basis, they???re
probably not getting into enough quality conversations.&lt;span&gt;&amp;nbsp; &lt;/span&gt;And if they can???t get into enough
conversations, they won???t generate the sales you need.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;o:p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/o:p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;Why not turn things around by looking at objections as a
natural part of the buying process that reveals a deeper level of interest and
curiosity on the part of the buyer?&lt;span&gt;&amp;nbsp; &lt;/span&gt;When
a sales professional looks at objections as a positive sign and is prepared to
listen and respond appropriately, the sale can proceed with ease.&lt;span&gt;&amp;nbsp; &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;o:p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/o:p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;How many objections does your team encounter?&lt;span&gt;&amp;nbsp; &lt;/span&gt;Why not spend 20 minutes at your next sales
meeting brainstorming all the objections they can think of ??? price, delivery,
lack of certain features, payment terms, and so on.&lt;span&gt;&amp;nbsp; &lt;/span&gt;Put them all up on a white board and when
your team runs out of ideas, spend the next 10 minutes making two new
lists.&lt;span&gt;&amp;nbsp; &lt;/span&gt;First, if there are objections
that could logically go together, put them into a broader category.&lt;span&gt;&amp;nbsp; &lt;/span&gt;When that???s done, ask your team to
rank the objections from most difficult to least difficult.&lt;span&gt;&amp;nbsp; &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;o:p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/o:p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;If you do this exercise right, your team should find there
are really only a handful of true objections, perhaps 6-8 all together.&lt;span&gt;&amp;nbsp; &lt;/span&gt;The words your sales people hear for each objection may
vary from prospect to prospect or situation to situation, but there should still only be a handful.&lt;span&gt;&amp;nbsp; &lt;/span&gt;Once
they???re all written down, ask somebody on your team to capture them in rank order and e-mail
it to the entire team.&lt;span&gt;&amp;nbsp; &lt;/span&gt;Then spend 10
minutes at each upcoming sales meeting going through one objection, from hardest to
easiest, until you are through the list.&amp;nbsp; Ask your team to share their ideas and best practices around how to overcome each objection
on the list.&lt;span&gt;&amp;nbsp; &lt;/span&gt;Put the objection list and best practices to handle them on your
sales wiki and ask people share any new ideas there.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;o:p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/o:p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;How much more prepared will your sales team be after they???ve
identified the most common objections they may face?&lt;span&gt;&amp;nbsp;
&lt;/span&gt;What will happen to their confidence as your team spends 10 minutes each
sales meeting sharing ideas and best practices on how to handle the toughest
objections?&lt;span&gt;&amp;nbsp; &lt;/span&gt;Why wait?&lt;span&gt;&amp;nbsp; &lt;/span&gt;Why not go through this exercise at your next
sales meeting?&amp;nbsp; Could you start this week?&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
</content>


