        <title>Sell Like a Three-Year Old</title>
        <link rel="alternate" type="text/html" href="http://www.intelligentconversations.com/b2b_sales_intelligent_con/2008/05/sell-like-a-three-year-old.html" />
        <link rel="replies" type="text/html" href="http://www.intelligentconversations.com/b2b_sales_intelligent_con/2008/05/sell-like-a-three-year-old.html" thr:count="0" />
        <id>tag:typepad.com,2003:post-50659708</id>
        <published>2008-05-31T17:12:45-05:00</published>
        <updated>2008-05-31T17:17:08-05:00</updated>
        <summary>How does a three-year old react to a stall, put-off or delay? Do they even hear ???let me think it over??? or ???no??? when you say it? And talk about being present and ???in the moment??? ??? how many three-year...</summary>
        <author>
            <name>mikecarroll</name>
        </author>
        <category scheme="http://www.sixapart.com/ns/types#category" term="Sales Coaching" />
        
        
<content type="xhtml" xml:lang="en-US" xml:base="http://www.intelligentconversations.com/b2b_sales_intelligent_con/">
<div xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"><p class="MsoNormal">How does a three-year old react to a stall, put-off or
delay?<span>&#0160; </span>Do they even hear ???let me think
it over??? or ???no??? when you say it?<span>&#0160; </span>And
talk about being present and ???in the moment??? ??? how many three-year olds worry
about tomorrow or next week or next quarter?<o:p> <br /></o:p></p>



<p class="MsoNormal">We can all learn from their presence and focus.<span>&#0160; </span>Their only concern is right here, right
now.<span>&#0160; </span>It???s wonderful.<span>&#0160; </span>They???re not checking their blackberry saying
???ok let???s see, I need to get in a nap this afternoon, play with blocks, get my
diaper changed and then finish that story Mom was reading last night.???<o:p> <br /></o:p></p>



<p class="MsoNormal">What would happen to your sales results if you could have
that same presence and focus?<span>&#0160; </span>There are
only so many times throughout the day when you are ???IN??? a sales conversation.
If you???re successful, you???re probably ???IN??? a lot of sales conversations.<span>&#0160; </span><o:p><br /></o:p></p>



<p class="MsoNormal">And when you are you need to be right here, right now,
present and focused on the moment.<span>&#0160;
</span>Nothing else matters except what the prospect or customer is
saying.<span>&#0160; </span>If you truly focus and listen ???
rather than worry about updating your pipeline report, revising your forecast,
completing your call reports, responding to e-mails, checking your text
messages, day dreaming, strategizing, analyzing, waiting for your turn to talk,
surfing the web, checking your watch, or any number of other distractions ???
you???ll have better conversations and your sales will improve.<o:p> <br /></o:p></p>

<p class="MsoNormal">It???s really that easy.<span>&#0160;
</span>Why not try it this week and see what happens?<span>&#0160; </span>Whenever you???re ???IN??? a sales conversation and
your mind starts to drift or you get distracted, take a deep breath and refocus
on the moment.<span>&#0160; </span>Sell like a three-year
old and watch your income grow.</p></div>
</content>


    </entry>
    <entry>
        <title>Slipping Margins</title>
        <link rel="alternate" type="text/html" href="http://www.intelligentconversations.com/b2b_sales_intelligent_con/2008/05/slipping-margins.html" />
        <link rel="replies" type="text/html" href="http://www.intelligentconversations.com/b2b_sales_intelligent_con/2008/05/slipping-margins.html" thr:count="0" />
        <id>tag:typepad.com,2003:post-50504258</id>
        <published>2008-05-28T07:33:32-05:00</published>
        <updated>2008-05-28T07:41:48-05:00</updated>
        <summary>How are your margins holding up? We???ve had several conversations recently with clients and prospects who are concerned about the impact slipping margins will have on their business this year. Is it really the economy driving down margins? Or is...</summary>
        <author>
            <name>mikecarroll</name>
        </author>
        <category scheme="http://www.sixapart.com/ns/types#category" term="Sales Management" />
        
        
<content type="xhtml" xml:lang="en-US" xml:base="http://www.intelligentconversations.com/b2b_sales_intelligent_con/">
<div xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"><p class="MsoNormal">How are your margins holding up?<span>&#0160; </span>We???ve had several conversations recently with
clients and prospects who are concerned about the impact slipping margins will
have on their business this year.<span>&#0160; </span>Is it
really the economy driving down margins? <span>&#0160;</span>Or is it the competition?<span>&#0160; </span>Maybe we should blame the Internet.<span>&#0160; </span>How about unreasonable clients who want to
commoditize your product or service?<span>&#0160; </span><st1:country-region w:st="on">China</st1:country-region>?&#0160; India?<span></span><span></span><span></span><o:p></o:p></p><p class="MsoNormal"><o:p></o:p>You can come up with all the excuses you want.<span>&#0160; </span>Or you can focus on the margin factors you
can control:</p>



<ul>
<li>Providing quality products and excellent service</li>
<li>Selecting a niche that allows you to be the best</li>
<li>Building and maintaining a great reputation</li>
<li>Developing great delivery systems</li>
<li>Making big promises and then over-delivering (Seth Godin???s <span style="text-decoration: underline;"><a href="http://sethgodin.typepad.com/seths_blog/2008/05/four-words.html">four
words</a>)</span></li>
<li>Firing your difficult customers</li>
<li>Hiring better sales people</li>
</ul>















<p class="MsoNormal"><o:p>L</o:p>et???s focus on this last one for a moment.<span>&#0160; </span>Do your sales people have a world view of
abundance or scarcity?<span>&#0160; </span>When they buy
things for themselves or their families, are they willing to pay more to get
what they really want?<span>&#0160; </span>Or do they shop
around and agonize about getting the lowest price?<span>&#0160; </span>If your sales people are in the latter
category, they completely understand and empathize with customers or prospects
who say ???you better sharpen your pencil.???<span>&#0160;
</span>(Dave Kurlan calls this a <a href="http://www.objectivemanagement.com/References/b.htm">Non-Supportive Buy Cycle</a><span class="-a" tag="a">)</span>.</p>



<p class="MsoNormal"><o:p></o:p>And your margins will keep slipping until your sales team
adopts an abundant mindset.<span>&#0160; </span>Want <a href="mailto:mike@intelligentconversations.com">help</a><span class="-a" tag="a">
</span>finding these sales people?<span>&#0160; </span>I can assure
you, they???re out there.<span>&#0160; </span>What would
happen to your margins if your entire sales team had an abundant world view?</p></div>
</content>


    </entry>
    <entry>
        <title>Expecting To Win</title>
        <link rel="alternate" type="text/html" href="http://www.intelligentconversations.com/b2b_sales_intelligent_con/2008/05/expecting-to-win.html" />
        <link rel="replies" type="text/html" href="http://www.intelligentconversations.com/b2b_sales_intelligent_con/2008/05/expecting-to-win.html" thr:count="0" />
        <id>tag:typepad.com,2003:post-50377670</id>
        <published>2008-05-25T07:47:32-05:00</published>
        <updated>2008-05-25T07:47:32-05:00</updated>
        <summary>Last weekend created a tough scenario for me as I watched my hometown Brewers take on my childhood Red Sox in Boston for an Inter-League series. Of course the Red Sox, with the second highest payroll in the majors, are...</summary>
        <author>
            <name>mikecarroll</name>
        </author>
        <category scheme="http://www.sixapart.com/ns/types#category" term="Sales Management" />
        
        
<content type="xhtml" xml:lang="en-US" xml:base="http://www.intelligentconversations.com/b2b_sales_intelligent_con/">
<div xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"><p class="MsoNormal">Last weekend created a tough scenario for me as I watched my
hometown Brewers take on my childhood Red Sox in <st1:city w:st="on"><st1:place w:st="on">Boston</st1:place></st1:city> for an Inter-League series.<span>&#0160; </span>Of course the Red Sox, with the second
highest payroll in the majors, are loaded with talent.<span>&#0160; </span>But the Brewers have built a nice nucleus of
young talent as well.<span>&#0160; </span><st1:city w:st="on"><st1:place w:st="on">Boston</st1:place></st1:city> swept the series, winning all three
games without difficulty.<o:p> <br /></o:p></p>



<p class="MsoNormal">At the end of the series, <st1:city w:st="on"><st1:place w:st="on">Milwaukee</st1:place></st1:city>???s star left fielder Ryan Braun
expressed concern about his team???s satisfaction with ???just competing??? with
the World Champion Red Sox.<span>&#0160; </span>He noted how
<st1:city w:st="on">Boston</st1:city> took the field ???expecting to win??? while <st1:city w:st="on"><st1:place w:st="on">Milwaukee</st1:place></st1:city> seemed to just
want to show they could compete.<span>&#0160; </span>How
often does your sales team expect to win?<span>&#0160;
</span>Are they satisfied with just being in the game and showing a good
effort?<o:p> <br /></o:p></p>



<p class="MsoNormal">Anybody can go through the motions ??? make cold calls, generate referrals, go to
appointments, ask questions, present proposals ??? but great sales people do
everything with the expectation that they???re going to win the business.<span>&#0160; </span>And they???ll do whatever it takes to win.<span>&#0160; </span>Is your sales team taking the field expecting
to win?<span>&#0160; </span>Or are they (like my hometown
Brewers) satisfied to simply be in the game?<span>&#0160; </span><o:p><br /></o:p></p>

<p class="MsoNormal">There are a lot of factors that go into whether or not your
company will win the business on any given deal, but one factor your can get
your arms around is your sales team and their attitude.<span>&#0160; </span>Are your expectations high enough?<span>&#0160; </span>Can you raise them during your next sales meeting?</p></div>
</content>


    </entry>
    <entry>
        <title>Productivity On Demand</title>
        <link rel="alternate" type="text/html" href="http://www.intelligentconversations.com/b2b_sales_intelligent_con/2008/05/productivity-on.html" />
        <link rel="replies" type="text/html" href="http://www.intelligentconversations.com/b2b_sales_intelligent_con/2008/05/productivity-on.html" thr:count="1" thr:updated="2008-05-20T14:26:29-05:00" />
        <id>tag:typepad.com,2003:post-50006130</id>
        <published>2008-05-17T16:01:04-05:00</published>
        <updated>2008-05-20T14:26:30-05:00</updated>
        <summary>We welcomed a newborn baby into our house about a week ago! Our intention is to adopt a child through the foster care system. After filling out all the paperwork, meeting with various social workers, completing the home study, and...</summary>
        <author>
            <name>mikecarroll</name>
        </author>
        <category scheme="http://www.sixapart.com/ns/types#category" term="Sales Coaching" />
        
        
<content type="html" xml:lang="en-US" xml:base="http://www.intelligentconversations.com/b2b_sales_intelligent_con/">
&lt;div xmlns=&quot;http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml&quot;&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;We welcomed a newborn baby into our house about a week
ago!&amp;nbsp; Our intention is to adopt a child
through the foster care system.&amp;nbsp; After
filling out all the paperwork, meeting with various social workers, completing
the home study, and finishing 36 hours of training, we became a licensed foster
home in mid-April.&amp;nbsp; Our expectations were
set for a toddler, 2-3 years old, so we lined up a day care provider from our
church and prepared our home for the new arrival.&lt;o:p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/o:p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;



&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;Well, as of last Friday we can throw those plans out the
window.&amp;nbsp; Instead of a toddler we???ve been
blessed with a beautiful healthy newborn baby. We???re all still adjusting to the changes this brings to our
household.&amp;nbsp; My biggest adjustment has
been learning to be productive on demand.&amp;nbsp; Because our foster child is a newborn, day care is not an option.&amp;nbsp; And because of my wife???s work schedule, I???m
the point person for watching our baby over the next few weeks. &lt;o:p&gt;&lt;/o:p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;



&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;Fortunately my work schedule is flexible, but it presents a
challenge when you know you???re going to have a limited window (i.e. when the
baby is sleeping) to make your cold calls and get your work done.&amp;nbsp; Talk about focus.&amp;nbsp; I???m using this as an opportunity to learn how
to be more productive with less time (and less sleep!).&amp;nbsp; My business development calls will need to
happen as they can during the brief windows I???m afforded during the day and the
work I need to do must get done during the evening hours when my wife is able
to watch our new baby.&amp;nbsp; Staying organized
is key to remaining effective and productive under these new work
circumstances.&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;Being highly focused, keeping a tight list of priorities and strictly adhering them is also essential.&amp;nbsp; This whole situation has created tremendous clarity around the activities I can stop doing.&lt;o:p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/o:p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;While I wouldn???t recommend bringing a newborn foster child
into your home as a catalyst for change, it does raise some interesting
questions.&amp;nbsp; What are you doing that you
don???t need to do? What could you do more
efficiently?&amp;nbsp; How can you get into your
cold calls more efficiently?&amp;nbsp; Can you
get off of your cold calls faster too?&amp;nbsp; What filters
are you using to set your priorities?&amp;nbsp; How focused are you?&amp;nbsp; What changes
can you make to your work habits that will increase your ???productivity on
demand????&amp;nbsp; Why not start today?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;/div&gt;
</content>


    </entry>
    <entry>
        <title>What Do You Do?</title>
        <link rel="alternate" type="text/html" href="http://www.intelligentconversations.com/b2b_sales_intelligent_con/2008/05/what-do-you-do.html" />
        <link rel="replies" type="text/html" href="http://www.intelligentconversations.com/b2b_sales_intelligent_con/2008/05/what-do-you-do.html" thr:count="0" />
        <id>tag:typepad.com,2003:post-49785904</id>
        <published>2008-05-13T05:37:27-05:00</published>
        <updated>2008-05-13T08:46:01-05:00</updated>
        <summary>How many times do you hear this question? Whether you???re at a business networking event, a conference or trade show, a seminar, or at your neighbor???s backyard barbeque, this is a common conversation starter. And the typical response generates common...</summary>
        <author>
            <name>mikecarroll</name>
        </author>
        <category scheme="http://www.sixapart.com/ns/types#category" term="Sales Coaching" />
        
        
<content type="html" xml:lang="en-US" xml:base="http://www.intelligentconversations.com/b2b_sales_intelligent_con/">
&lt;div xmlns=&quot;http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml&quot;&gt;

&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;How many times do you hear this question?&amp;nbsp; Whether you???re at a business networking
event, a conference or trade show, a seminar, or at your neighbor???s backyard
barbeque, this is a common conversation starter.&amp;nbsp; And the typical response generates common
(i.e. boring, unproductive, and short) conversations.&lt;o:p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/o:p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;



&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;???So Adam, what do you do????&lt;o:p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/o:p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;



&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;???I???m a __________ (fill in your professional category). How about you????&lt;o:p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/o:p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;



&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;???I work for a ____________ (fill in your company???s
industrial category).???&lt;o:p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/o:p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;



&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;And the conversation typically ends right there or goes on
for a few awkward questions.&lt;o:p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/o:p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;



&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;Instead, why not have a more engaging answer prepared?&amp;nbsp; You know you???re going to be asked this
question frequently, so why not prepare a loose outline that allows you to
generate more lively, engaging and productive conversations?&lt;o:p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/o:p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;



&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;???So Adam, what do you do????&lt;o:p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/o:p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;



&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;???Thanks for asking Tim. Do you know how ____________ (state a compelling problem you solve)????&lt;o:p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/o:p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;



&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;???Yes, I know ???.???&lt;o:p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/o:p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;



&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;Well, I work with ______________ (describe the people or
executives who have the problem you just stated) to ________________ (describe
how you help).&amp;nbsp; The results are
_________________ (state the results as specifically as possible).&lt;o:p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/o:p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;



&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;And the conversations goes on from there, but this time the
person asking the initial question has a lot more information and a better idea
of exactly what you do.&amp;nbsp; If I???m asked
this question, it might go something like this:&lt;o:p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/o:p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;



&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;???So Mike, what do you do????&lt;o:p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/o:p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;



&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;???Thank you for asking. Do you know how some sales people struggle to produce results while
others seem to make their numbers effortlessly????&lt;o:p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/o:p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;



&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;???Yes, that sounds like our sales team.???&lt;o:p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/o:p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;



&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;???Well, I work with Presidents, CEOs and Business Owners to help
determine if they have the right sales people on their team and to figure out
what???s holding some of their sales people back.&amp;nbsp; We typically identify opportunities for improvement that can increase
revenue by 65% over two years???&lt;o:p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/o:p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;The key to making this work is to keep it conversational and
loosely structured.&amp;nbsp; Once you get the
basic format down you???ll be able to easily adjust and modify your response on
the fly as you grow more comfortable with it.&amp;nbsp; Remember, the goal is to have a real conversation not just recite a
script (which will be a very obvious conversation killer). &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;If you create your response, how
much more productive will your networking conversations be?&amp;nbsp; How many conversations can you have this
week?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;/div&gt;
</content>


    </entry>
    <entry>
        <title>A Bias for Action</title>
        <link rel="alternate" type="text/html" href="http://www.intelligentconversations.com/b2b_sales_intelligent_con/2008/05/a-bias-for-acti.html" />
        <link rel="replies" type="text/html" href="http://www.intelligentconversations.com/b2b_sales_intelligent_con/2008/05/a-bias-for-acti.html" thr:count="0" />
        <id>tag:typepad.com,2003:post-49519526</id>
        <published>2008-05-07T07:47:02-05:00</published>
        <updated>2008-05-07T07:50:27-05:00</updated>
        <summary>Sometimes you just have to get going. We???re working with a client on their positioning statements and question funnels. It???s all new to them and I sense their frustration level is getting higher and higher as they attempt this new...</summary>
        <author>
            <name>mikecarroll</name>
        </author>
        <category scheme="http://www.sixapart.com/ns/types#category" term="Sales Coaching" />
        
        
<content type="html" xml:lang="en-US" xml:base="http://www.intelligentconversations.com/b2b_sales_intelligent_con/">
&lt;div xmlns=&quot;http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml&quot;&gt;



&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;Sometimes you just have to get going.&amp;nbsp; We???re working with a client on their
positioning statements and question funnels.&amp;nbsp; It???s all new to them and I sense their frustration level is getting
higher and higher as they attempt this new approach.&amp;nbsp; What???s holding them back?&amp;nbsp; I think
it???s their belief that it has to be perfect.&lt;o:p&gt;&lt;/o:p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;o:p&gt;&lt;/o:p&gt;They want to have ???perfect??? role playing exercises where
everything flows just right.&amp;nbsp; Each
question is answered in a way that reveals a need and as they go through the question
funnel they are able to develop a long list of compelling reasons to move
forward in the sales process.&amp;nbsp; Everything is flawless.&amp;nbsp; And they
actually approach perfection during the role playing drills.&lt;o:p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/o:p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;



&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;Problem is, when they get on the phone with real prospects
the conversation falls apart.&amp;nbsp; The busy
decision makers they reach don???t follow the script.&amp;nbsp; They ask different questions.&amp;nbsp; They raise new objections.&amp;nbsp; They take the dialog out of sequence.&amp;nbsp; And they are much more impatient and
demanding ??? ???Get to the point!???&lt;o:p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/o:p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;



&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;The reality is it???s nearly impossible to have ???the perfect
sales conversation.???&amp;nbsp; You just need to
have enough questions to ask and enough insights to share to keep the
conversation going.&amp;nbsp; Don???t get hung up on
making it perfect, just get out there and start having conversations.&amp;nbsp; A bias for action will get you into more
conversations, faster.&amp;nbsp; And the more
sales conversations you have the better you???ll get at it.&amp;nbsp; If you make a mistake, big deal.&amp;nbsp; Just let it go and move onto the next call
with ease and confidence.&lt;o:p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/o:p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;What will happen to your results if you replace a bias for
perfection with a bias for action?&amp;nbsp; Why
not start today?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;/div&gt;
</content>


    </entry>
 
